So, what about this person?

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:59.430
That's me -- this is my college
yearbook photo.

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:01.620
OK, what about this
person over here?

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:06.610
STUDENT: You?

00:02:06.610 --> 00:02:09.850
PROFESSOR: It's not me again.

00:02:09.850 --> 00:02:12.310
Not Elizabeth Taylor.

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:23.750
It is Lisa Kudrow, known as
Phoebe on "Friends." So, we

00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:26.450
both went to college at
the same time, we

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:27.690
went to the same college.

00:02:27.690 --> 00:02:33.160
Does anybody know what
college that was?

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:33.510
STUDENT: Vassar.

00:02:33.510 --> 00:02:35.430
PROFESSOR: Vassar College,
very good.

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:39.540
And we graduated the same year
-- now no one has to say what

00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:42.400
year that was, even if
you know, but we did

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:44.290
graduate the same year.

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:45.170
All right.

00:02:45.170 --> 00:02:51.780
So, given what you know about
us, what do you think Lisa

00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:53.280
went to college to study?

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:56.750
STUDENT: Computer?

00:02:56.750 --> 00:02:58.200
PROFESSOR: Computers?

00:02:58.200 --> 00:02:59.650
No.

00:02:59.650 --> 00:03:00.420
STUDENT: Theatre?

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:00.880
PROFESSOR: Theatre?

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:01.650
Surprisingly, no.

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:02.710
STUDENT: Nuclear Engineering?

00:03:02.710 --> 00:03:04.520
PROFESSOR: Nuclear Engineering
at Vassar, no for

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:08.120
a variety of reasons.

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:08.940
Any other guesses?

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:11.040
STUDENT: English?

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:11.720
PROFESSOR: English, no.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:13.280
Biology --

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:15.260
I heard it.

00:03:15.260 --> 00:03:16.990
Biology.

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:19.670
What do you think I went
to college to study?

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:21.750
STUDENT: Theatre.

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:24.670
PROFESSOR: Theatre, correct!

00:03:24.670 --> 00:03:28.610
And/or I hadn't made up
my mind exactly --

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:31.300
biopsychology or drama.

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:33.920
So, biopsychology was what they
called sort of brain and

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:36.530
cognitive sciences
in those days.

00:03:36.530 --> 00:03:40.580
So, those were the two things
I was thinking about.

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:44.000
What do you think Lisa ended
up majoring in college?

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.490
STUDENT: Biopsychology.

00:03:46.490 --> 00:03:50.210
PROFESSOR: Not biopsychology.

00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:50.490
STUDENT: Biology.

00:03:50.490 --> 00:03:57.180
PROFESSOR: Biology, yes.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:59.000
What do you think I majored
in college?

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:00.060
This should be a bit easier.

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:01.300
STUDENT: Chemistry.

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:05.660
PROFESSOR: Chemistry, And, of
course, our professions,

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:09.160
actress and chemistry
professor.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:15.960
So, let me ask what
happened here?

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:19.410
My understanding about Lisa
Kudrow is that she came from a

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:20.770
Hollywood family.

00:04:20.770 --> 00:04:23.650
She went to college and said
here's my opportunity to study

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:26.390
the thing that I find most
interesting, and that was

00:04:26.390 --> 00:04:29.490
biology, and then she went back
and participated in the

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:33.450
family business, which was of
course the acting profession.

00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:35.410
For me, what happened?

00:04:35.410 --> 00:04:42.220
Well, I have to say, I did not
like chemistry in high school,

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:45.920
so I did not think about going
to college to study chemistry.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:50.010
So, why did I not like chemistry
in high school?

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:56.420
I think it was because of
images such as this one.

00:04:56.420 --> 00:04:58.730
You spend a lot of time talking
about the transition

00:04:58.730 --> 00:05:00.680
between alchemy and
modern chemistry.

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:03.580
I wasn't very interested in
that kind of thing, and

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:05.870
there's nothing in these
photographs that really

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:07.810
appealed to me personally.

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:08.690
I mean, Avogadro --

00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:14.050
I'm fond of his number, and he
is, in fact, an interesting,

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:18.770
if not frightening looking
man -- this just didn't

00:05:18.770 --> 00:05:21.160
connect with me.

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:23.130
But then I got to college and
they said, "Well, if you're

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:26.950
thinking about anything bio --
biopsychology, biology -- you

00:05:26.950 --> 00:05:31.890
have to take chemistry." And I
said to my advisor, "No, no.

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:35.530
I have taken chemistry in high
school, and I can assure you

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:38.500
that chemistry has no relevance
whatsoever to the

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:42.210
life sciences." And they said,
"Well, I'm sorry you feel that

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:46.010
way, it's incorrect, and you
have to take it anyway."

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:51.120
So, I, like some of you in
this room, took freshman

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:54.870
chemistry, because we had to,
not because we wanted to.

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:58.540
And I, like hopefully some of
you in this room, discovered

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:01.620
that chemistry was actually
a lot of fun, and that the

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:05.030
chemistry I got in college was
pretty much nothing like the

00:06:05.030 --> 00:06:07.780
chemistry I had seen
in high school.

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:09.930
So, let me introduce you to
some of the topics we are

00:06:09.930 --> 00:06:14.590
going to be covering in
chemistry this semester.

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:18.470
So, there's more detail on your
syllabus -- a detail of

00:06:18.470 --> 00:06:20.810
what we'll cover every day,
but these are the kind of

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:23.010
basic things that were covering,
and you don't need

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:25.060
to write this down, you'll
become familiar with it as the

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:27.280
semester goes on.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:29.900
We start out with some really
basic principles.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:34.050
So, up here, atomic theory,
periodic table, bonding,

00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:35.560
structures and molecules.

00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:40.990
And there will be a little bit
of history in there, but this

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:45.330
is mostly modern chemistry
and represents the basic

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:48.960
properties of matter, and it's
basic properties of all

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:51.860
matter, including living matter,
which was what really

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:55.070
interested me, that connection
between chemistry and biology.

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:57.050
So, then we go to thermodynamics
and chemical

00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:00.850
equilibrium, and this is
really about chemical

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:04.051
reactions -- weather a reaction
will go, will it be

00:07:04.051 --> 00:07:06.330
spontaneous, if there an
equilibrium, what direction

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:09.590
will the reaction
be shifted in.

00:07:09.590 --> 00:07:12.350
And then, of course, not just
whether the reaction will

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:15.830
occur but, how fast it occurs
is really important.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:19.500
So, that's kinetics -- how fast
a reaction will go, and

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:21.910
from the perspective of someone
who's a biochemist,

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:25.350
I'm interested in kinetics and
enzyme kinetics, and thinking

00:07:25.350 --> 00:07:29.060
about molecules that catalyze
reactions in the body.

00:07:29.060 --> 00:07:31.760
And then, there's acid base
equilibrium, and also

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:36.030
oxidation reduction reactions,
and what is true is that most

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:38.100
reactions that occur are either
catalyzed by either

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:40.880
some kind of acid base catalysis
or involve some kind

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:44.510
of oxidation reduction reaction,
and so, this sort of

00:07:44.510 --> 00:07:50.100
represents a lot of the basic
way reactions go -- now,

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.830
whether that's a reaction in
your body or a reaction in a

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:54.790
test tube -- it doesn't matter,
a lot of the same

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:56.450
principles are involved.

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:58.620
And then, we also cover
transition metals, which is

00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:01.570
something that you often don't
see in high school.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:04.060
And transition metals, those
all medals in the middle of

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.240
your periodic table, have some
really unique properties,

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:09.840
which are exploited again in
reactions that occur in your

00:08:09.840 --> 00:08:13.270
body, and also are utilized in
industry, for example, so

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:15.960
we'll talk about some of those
unique properties.

00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:20.090
And if we put all of that
together, we get the real

00:08:20.090 --> 00:08:22.650
fundamentals that you need to go
on and study -- any kind of

00:08:22.650 --> 00:08:24.710
curriculum that involves
chemistry.

00:08:24.710 --> 00:08:28.440
So, these are all the
fundamentals that are involved

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:31.630
in chemistry that relate to
physical chemistry, organic

00:08:31.630 --> 00:08:34.670
chemistry, inorganic chemistry,
biological

00:08:34.670 --> 00:08:37.040
chemistry, and are a solid
foundation for studying any

00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:38.510
kind of life science.

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:41.880
So, I congratulate you of being
here in this class, this

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:44.830
is really good solid foundation
for whatever you go

00:08:44.830 --> 00:08:47.460
on to do, here at MIT.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:50.900
So, normally at this point, we
do actually start class with a

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:54.760
little bit of history from
alchemy to modern chemistry,

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:58.040
but I decided to skip
that this year.

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:00.680
If you are interested in that,
it's never required on any

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:04.140
test, it never has been, but if
you're interested in that

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:08.070
there is an OCW lecture, which
you can listen to that's an

00:09:08.070 --> 00:09:10.580
excellent lecture by Professor
Sylvia Ceyer on that.

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:13.800
But today instead, I thought I
would give you some examples

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:18.500
of modern chemistry -- why
people now need to know

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:21.200
chemistry, what they're doing
with chemistry, what is

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:25.330
chemistry research here at MIT,
and how does it utilize

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:27.590
these basic principles,
which we'll be talking

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:29.420
about in the course.

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:31.870
So, I'll start with
my colleague,

00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:33.620
Professor Joanne Stubbe.

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:35.680
She studies molecules, in
particular she studies

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:37.500
biological molecules.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:40.310
And, so one of the things she's
very interested in is

00:09:40.310 --> 00:09:43.470
how this anti-cancer
drug, gemcitabine,

00:09:43.470 --> 00:09:45.270
works in the body.

00:09:45.270 --> 00:09:48.020
So, it inhibits an enzyme, and
she's interested in knowing

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:49.620
how that really works.

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:52.690
So, enzymes are made up of amino
acids, you have long

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:55.980
chains of amino acids that form
together into a protein

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:58.710
molecules, protein molecules
in your body often act as

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:00.880
enzymes, catalyzing reactions.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.820
So, she is interested in how
this molecule, gemcitabine,

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:06.380
inhibits an enzyme.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:09.455
So, to do those studies, she
needs to know a lot of the

00:10:09.455 --> 00:10:10.510
stuff on this list.

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:13.170
Of course, she needs to know
the basic principles, but

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:15.430
she's also talking about it an
enzyme, so she needs to know

00:10:15.430 --> 00:10:17.490
about enzyme catalysis.

00:10:17.490 --> 00:10:21.290
She needs to know this enzyme
works by both acid base

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:23.220
chemistry, and oxidation
reduction.

00:10:23.220 --> 00:10:26.980
It has two irons that are
involved in doing the

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:29.610
chemistry, so it includes
transition metals.

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.450
She thinks about how things
bind, how the natural

00:10:32.450 --> 00:10:35.230
reactants binds, how the
inhibitor binds, and so she

00:10:35.230 --> 00:10:37.482
needs to know what happens to
the chemical equilibrium, she

00:10:37.482 --> 00:10:39.170
needs to know about the
thermodynamics of those

00:10:39.170 --> 00:10:42.280
binding events, and, of course,
everything, all the

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:44.620
basic principles, are
required here.

00:10:44.620 --> 00:10:48.380
So, to do this biochemistry
research, she needs to know

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:52.330
all of these things, and she
has really made tremendous

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:55.040
progress in understanding how
gemcitabine works, and it is

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:59.860
not so toxic, so it's a really
good thing to have in

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:01.770
chemotherapy.

00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:04.860
So, in addition to studying
molecules, chemists often want

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:07.890
to make molecules, such
as Tim Jamison,

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:09.940
who's an organic chemist.

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:14.170
So, you will hear, probably,
hopefully, in this

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:17.470
presidential debate about the
environment and about why

00:11:17.470 --> 00:11:19.290
saving the environment
is important.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:21.480
And one of the things you
often hear about in this

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:25.340
discussion is about our oceans
and about rainforests, and

00:11:25.340 --> 00:11:28.740
part of the reason why people
want to protect those areas is

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:30.740
because you find a
lot of natural

00:11:30.740 --> 00:11:32.480
products in those regions.

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:34.530
So, a natural product is
something that is made by

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:36.880
nature, and often natural
products, whether it comes

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:39.960
from a plant or a marine
organism have some really

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:41.730
good, useful properties.

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:45.330
And so, one particular compound
has anti-tumor

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:45.790
properties.

00:11:45.790 --> 00:11:48.760
So, again, along this line
of cancer research.

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:51.850
So, Tim Jamison's lab figured
out how to make this thing.

00:11:51.850 --> 00:11:55.300
And often that's really
important, because you can't

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:58.920
get enough of the organism that
naturally makes it, to be

00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:01.670
able to grind that organism up
and have enough that you can

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:03.030
actually use as a medicine.

00:12:03.030 --> 00:12:06.040
So, you have to make more of
it, because nature doesn't

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:06.850
make enough.

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:10.290
So, it's very important to
figure out how to do that.

00:12:10.290 --> 00:12:14.120
So, in doing that, Tim Jamison's
lab needs a lot of

00:12:14.120 --> 00:12:15.250
these things.

00:12:15.250 --> 00:12:18.610
So, he needs a lot of knowledge
of bonding, he wants

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:20.370
to form bonds in making this.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.700
He needs to know about the
structures of the molecules,

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:25.920
because if the structure is
wrong it's not going to work.

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:28.060
And often, if you want to make a
lot of it, you have to think

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:29.870
about the thermodynamics of
the system, how fast the

00:12:29.870 --> 00:12:32.380
reactions will go and kinetics,
and then whether

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:33.885
they'll go, the thermodynamics,
and sometimes

00:12:33.885 --> 00:12:40.130
then you need to adjust the
reactions, maybe use a

00:12:40.130 --> 00:12:42.190
transition metal to
make it go better.

00:12:42.190 --> 00:12:45.810
So, these are all the things
that Tim Jamison needs to know

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:47.110
to do organic chemistry.

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:50.000
So, you'll be learning in this
class a great preparation for

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.280
512, which is organic
chemistry.

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:56.250
In addition to studying
molecules and making

00:12:56.250 --> 00:13:00.590
molecules, some chemists want
to detect molecules, and a

00:13:00.590 --> 00:13:04.250
chemist who likes to detect
molecules is Tim Swager.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:07.800
So, Tim Swager's lab has
designed sensors that detect

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:11.590
