could actually, using my
chemical knowledge, think

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:38.100
about synthesizing these
molecules, or maybe coming up

00:25:38.100 --> 00:25:41.150
with new ways to synthesize
them better or synthesize

00:25:41.150 --> 00:25:42.380
different molecules.

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:46.170
And the real clincher was when
I started doing some

00:25:46.170 --> 00:25:47.960
undergraduate research.

00:25:47.960 --> 00:25:51.620
Any potential UROPs out there
-- anyone planning to do a

00:25:51.620 --> 00:25:53.690
research at some point?

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:54.420
Excellent.

00:25:54.420 --> 00:25:55.870
Okay.

00:25:55.870 --> 00:25:58.430
So, just to be warned, you might
fall in love with the

00:25:58.430 --> 00:26:00.490
subject you do your UROP in.

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:02.690
This is one of our summer
students from this past

00:26:02.690 --> 00:26:04.270
summer, who is also premed.

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:07.180
She's continuing to be pre-med,
which is fantastic.

00:26:07.180 --> 00:26:09.430
That didn't happen to me --
once I got into the lab, I

00:26:09.430 --> 00:26:10.250
didn't want to leave.

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:12.880
So, I thought, "You know what,
I think I'll change the

00:26:12.880 --> 00:26:15.020
medical school plans and now I'm
going to go all the way --

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:18.030
chemistry major, chemistry grad
school." And the reason I

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:20.920
was able to do that and keep
with what my original

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:23.120
intentions were was to have
a career that was the

00:26:23.120 --> 00:26:25.510
fulfilling, in terms of helping
people and being

00:26:25.510 --> 00:26:28.880
engaged in science, is all of
a sudden I realized, as

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:32.910
chemists, we can think about
better ways to build molecules

00:26:32.910 --> 00:26:35.400
that are important for
making medications.

00:26:35.400 --> 00:26:38.450
Another thing we can do is we
can use our chemistry to

00:26:38.450 --> 00:26:41.650
understand biological systems,
so we can help illucinate

00:26:41.650 --> 00:26:44.440
pathways, maybe, that are
implicated in disease.

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:46.740
So, the combination of these
two things had made my

00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:49.340
decision and I ended up coming
here for graduate school,

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:52.840
actually, and working in
Professor Imperiali's lab

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:56.850
doing bio-organic chemistry,
which means that I synthesize

00:26:56.850 --> 00:26:59.710
molecules, which I loved,
and used them to

00:26:59.710 --> 00:27:01.620
study biological systems.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:05.060
So, really I'm pretty happy with
what I've gotten to do,

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:07.620
and I just want to say we're not
trying to convert all of

00:27:07.620 --> 00:27:11.050
them you pre-med people,
by any means.

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:14.220
My roommate for many years was
going to medical school as I

00:27:14.220 --> 00:27:17.330
was going to graduate school,
and we found we had so many

00:27:17.330 --> 00:27:19.920
interesting conversations about
chemistry -- her from

00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:24.300
the context of practicing and
using medications and talking

00:27:24.300 --> 00:27:26.590
about how they worked on a
molecular level, and me

00:27:26.590 --> 00:27:28.590
talking about my research.

